df -h : to check how much disk space is used and how much is free on your system -in human readble fom(like MB GB)
  exampls:
  renuka@Bunny:/$ df -h
Filesystem      Size  Used Avail Use% Mounted on
rootfs          458G   81G  378G  18% /
none            458G   81G  378G  18% /dev
none            458G   81G  378G  18% /run
none            458G   81G  378G  18% /run/lock
none            458G   81G  378G  18% /run/shm
none            458G   81G  378G  18% /run/user
cgroup          458G   81G  378G  18% /sys/fs/cgroup
C:\             458G   81G  378G  18% /mnt/c
D:\             458G  111M  458G   1% /mnt/d
---  --------------------------------------------
  du -h : du stands for disk usage
 it shows the disk usage of files and directories in a format easy for humans to read
ex:
renuka@Bunny:~$ du -h
0       ./.config/procps
0       ./.config
0       ./.landscape
0       ./.local/share/nano
0       ./.local/share
0       ./.local
0       ./renu
20K     .
KEY DIFFERENCE BETWEEN du -h and df -h:
du-h is folder focused
df -h is disk focused
-----------------------------------------
du -sh >> sumary only (don't show all subfolders)
renuka@Bunny:~$ du -sh
20K    
du -sh * >> shows a quick overview of sizes of all folers/files in your current location
renuka@Bunny:~$ du -sh *
0       p1.txt
0       p2.txt
0       p3.txt
0       renu
du -ah  >> shows all files and folders
 DIFFERNECE BETWEN du -h and du -ah
du -h >> folders only'
 du -ah >> folders + files                       
one best example:
suppose your /documets directory looks like this
/Documents
│
├── notes
│   └── todo.txt  (4K)
│
├── projects
│   └── project1.zip  (1.2M)
│
└── reports
    └── report.pdf  (500K)    
now using du -h 
4.0K    /Documents/notes
1.2M    /Documents/projects
500K    /Documents/reports
5.7M    /Documents
>>> shows only folders
>>> no induvidual file listed
>> the last line give the total folder size 
now using du -ah 
4.0K    /Documents/notes/todo.txt
4.0K    /Documents/notes
1.2M    /Documents/projects/project1.zip
1.2M    /Documents/projects
500K    /Documents/reports/report.pdf
500K    /Documents/reports
5.7M    /Documents    
shows both folders and files 
each file size is disaplayed induvidually
-------------------------------------------------------------
 du -sh * | sort -h

du -sh * → Shows the total size of each folder/file in the current directory (summary, human-readable).

| sort -h → Sorts the output by size, smallest to largest.
 du -sh * | sort -hr
 -r reverse order
example:
renuka@Bunny:~$ touch p1.txt p2.txt p3.txt
renuka@Bunny:~$ ls -l
total 0
-rw-rw-rw- 1 renuka renuka    0 Oct 23 14:29 p1.txt
-rw-rw-rw- 1 renuka renuka    0 Oct 23 14:29 p2.txt
-rw-rw-rw- 1 renuka renuka    0 Oct 23 14:29 p3.txt
drwxrwxrwx 1 renuka renuka 4096 Oct 23 13:22 renu
renuka@Bunny:~$ fallocate -l 3k p3.txt
renuka@Bunny:~$ fallocate -l 2m p2.txt
renuka@Bunny:~$ fallocate -l 1k p1.txt
renuka@Bunny:~$ ls -lh >> ls -lh for exact file sizes:( i have used la -l(not human readable) but i got reslut for 1k its 1024 to get exacccccccct use ls-lh(human readable like kb gb mb)
total 2.1M
-rw-rw-rw- 1 renuka renuka 1.0K Oct 23 14:29 p1.txt
-rw-rw-rw- 1 renuka renuka 2.0M Oct 23 14:29 p2.txt
-rw-rw-rw- 1 renuka renuka 3.0K Oct 23 14:29 p3.txt
drwxrwxrwx 1 renuka renuka 4.0K Oct 23 13:22 renu
renuka@Bunny:~$ du -sh * | sort -h
0       renu
4.0K    p1.txt
4.0K    p3.txt
2.0M    p2.txt
renuka@Bunny:~$ du -sh * | sort -hr
2.0M    p2.txt
4.0K    p3.txt
4.0K    p1.txt
0       renu 
-----------------------------------------------
ncdu /home/renuka
Provides an interactive, text-based interface to explore disk usage.
Lets you see folder sizes, drill down, and even delete files/folders directly from the interface.                                                       
Navigate using arrow keys
Press Enter to go into a folder
Press d to delete a selected folder/file
-----------------------------------------------
mount 
mount is used to attach a storage device or partition (like a USB, external hard disk, CD, or even a Windows drive) to the Linux filesystem so you can access its data.

Think of it like connecting a new road to your city — only after connecting (mounting), you can travel (access) that area.
renuka@Bunny:~$ mount
rootfs on / type lxfs (rw,noatime)
none on /dev type tmpfs (rw,noatime,mode=755)
sysfs on /sys type sysfs (rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,noatime)
proc on /proc type proc (rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,noatime)
devpts on /dev/pts type devpts (rw,nosuid,noexec,noatime,gid=5,mode=620)
none on /run type tmpfs (rw,nosuid,noexec,noatime,mode=755)
none on /run/lock type tmpfs (rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,noatime)
none on /run/shm type tmpfs (rw,nosuid,nodev,noatime)
none on /run/user type tmpfs (rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,noatime,mode=755)
binfmt_misc on /proc/sys/fs/binfmt_misc type binfmt_misc (rw,relatime)
tmpfs on /sys/fs/cgroup type tmpfs (rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,relatime,mode=755)
cgroup on /sys/fs/cgroup/devices type cgroup (rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,relatime,devices)
C:\ on /mnt/c type drvfs (rw,noatime,uid=1000,gid=1000,case=off)
D:\ on /mnt/d type drvfs (rw,noatime,uid=1000,gid=1000,case=off)

O/P means :[DEVICE] on [MOUNT POINT] type [FILESYSTEM] (OPTIONS)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
You can check what’s inside your Windows drives directly:
cd /mnt/c
ls
o/p:
renuka@Bunny:~$ cd /mnt/c
renuka@Bunny:/mnt/c$ ls
ls: cannot access 'DumpStack.log.tmp': Permission denied (Those warnings are normal — they just mean:“You don’t have permission to read these system-protected Windows files.”)
ls: cannot access 'hiberfil.sys': Permission denied
ls: cannot access 'pagefile.sys': Permission denied
ls: cannot access 'swapfile.sys': Permission denied
'$Recycle.Bin'  'Documents and Settings'   DumpStack.log.tmp   PerfLogs               ProgramData                  Users         dell           inetpub        tmp
'$WinREAgent'    Drivers                   Intel              'Program Files'         Recovery                     Windows       dell.sdr       pagefile.sys
 Apps            DummyDir                  OneDriveTemp       'Program Files (x86)'  'System Volume Information'   Windows.old   hiberfil.sys   swapfile.sys
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
if you want to mount manually:
sudo mkdir /mnt/testmount >> create a folder
ls /mnt >> to check weather its created or not
renuka@Bunny:/$ ls /mnt
c  d  testmount
sudo mount --bind /mnt/c /mnt/testmount
--bind is a safe method to remount an existing folder elsewhere.
Here, you’re telling Linux:
“Show me everything from /mnt/c also at /mnt/testmount.
O/P:
renuka@Bunny:/$ sudo mount --bind /mnt/c /mnt/testmount
renuka@Bunny:/$ ls /mnt/testmount >> to check the contents
ls: cannot access '/mnt/testmount/DumpStack.log.tmp': Permission denied
ls: cannot access '/mnt/testmount/hiberfil.sys': Permission denied
ls: cannot access '/mnt/testmount/pagefile.sys': Permission denied
ls: cannot access '/mnt/testmount/swapfile.sys': Permission denied
'$Recycle.Bin'  'Documents and Settings'   DumpStack.log.tmp   PerfLogs               ProgramData                  Users         dell           inetpub        tmp
'$WinREAgent'    Drivers                   Intel              'Program Files'         Recovery                     Windows       dell.sdr       pagefile.sys
 Apps            DummyDir                  OneDriveTemp       'Program Files (x86)'  'System Volume Information'   Windows.old   hiberfil.sys   swapfile.sys
------------------------------------
to verify if it is really mounted :
mount | grep testmount
O/P:
renuka@Bunny:/$ mount | grep testmount
C:\ on /mnt/testmount type drvfs (rw,noatime,uid=1000,gid=1000,case=off)
---------------------------------
To unmount :
sudo umount /mnt/testmount
to check weather its there or not
renuka@Bunny:/$ ls /mnt/testmount
KEY POINT:
why we used sudo here?
We use sudo with mount because:
Mounting and unmounting devices affects the entire system, not just your user.
So only the root (administrator) has permission to do it.
-------------------------------------------
findmnt:
It’s like mount, but much easier to read, especially if you have many mounts.
renuka@Bunny:/$ findmnt
TARGET                       SOURCE      FSTYPE      OPTIONS
/                            rootfs      lxfs        rw,noatime
├─/dev                       none        tmpfs       rw,noatime,mode=755
│ └─/dev/pts                 devpts      devpts      rw,nosuid,noexec,noatime,gid=5,mode=620
├─/sys                       sysfs       sysfs       rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,noatime
│ └─/sys/fs/cgroup           tmpfs       tmpfs       rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,relatime,mode=755
│   └─/sys/fs/cgroup/devices cgroup      cgroup      rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,relatime,devices
├─/proc                      proc        proc        rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,noatime
│ └─/proc/sys/fs/binfmt_misc binfmt_misc binfmt_misc rw,relatime
├─/run                       none        tmpfs       rw,nosuid,noexec,noatime,mode=755
│ ├─/run/lock                none        tmpfs       rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,noatime
│ ├─/run/shm                 none        tmpfs       rw,nosuid,nodev,noatime
│ └─/run/user                none        tmpfs       rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,noatime,mode=755
├─/mnt/c                     C:\         drvfs       rw,noatime,uid=1000,gid=1000,case=off
└─/mnt/d                     D:\         drvfs       rw,noatime,uid=1000,gid=1000,case=off

  
  
